\begin_layout Standard
You might have noticed that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=wx+b$
\end_inset

 is not a linear function in the strict sense.
 Only 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=wx$
\end_inset

 is a linear function since any linear function must take the value zero
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=wx+b$
\end_inset

 are called 
\emph on

\begin_inset LatexCommand index
name "affine functions"

\end_inset

affine functions
\emph default
.
 However, since 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)=w$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the linear approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=wx+b$
\end_inset

 is also ambiguously called linear approximation, even though it is not
 a linear function for 
\begin_inset Formula $b\not=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is just one last generalization left, that we have to take care of
 : If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\not=0$
\end_inset

, then we cannot simply choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
g(x_{0}) & = & wx_{0}+b\\
 & = & f'(x_{0})x_{0}+f(x_{0})\\
 & \not= & f(x_{o})\mbox{\mbox{for }}w,x_{0}\not=0.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

However, we can fix this by a simple trick: We just subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $wx_{0}=f'(x_{0})x_{0}$
\end_inset

 to enforce 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_{0})=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 By this, we arrive at the general form of a linear approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 for at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
g(x) & = & wx+b\\
 & = & f'(x_{0})x+f(x_{0})-f'(x_{o})x_{0}\\
 & = & f(x_{0})+(x-x_{o})f'(x_{o}).\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quality of the approximation depends, of course, on the properties of
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, in the example above, the approximation is really bad for e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pi.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The linear approximation to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{o}=0$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
g_{0}(x) & = & f(x)+(x-x_{o})f'(x_{o})\\
 & = & e^{0}+x\cdot e^{0}\\
 & = & 1+x.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The approximation at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{o}=1$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
g_{1}(x) & = & f(x)+(x-x_{o})f'(x_{o})\\
 & = & e^{1}+(x-1)\cdot e^{1}\\
 & = & xe.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

